<p><strong>Pros:</strong> Significantly higher potential. A well-managed unit in a prime location (like Avenue-by-the-Sea or near Jonker Street) can achieve <strong>6-10% yield</strong> or more.</p>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong> Fluctuating income. Some months (like school holidays) are booming; others (like Ramadan) might be slower.</p>

<h2>2. Flexibility & Control</h2>

<h3>Long-Term Rental</h3>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong> Set it and forget it (mostly).</p>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong> You lose access to your property. You can't use it for your own vacations. Evicting a bad tenant is a legal nightmare.</p>

<h3>Short-Term Rental</h3>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong> Complete control. Block out dates for your own family holidays. If a guest breaks rules, they're gone in days, not months.</p>
<p><strong>Cons:</strong> High turnover means constant management (unless you hire a pro).</p>

<h2>3. Property Condition</h2>

<h3>Long-Term Rental</h3>
<p><strong>Risk:</strong> Tenants rarely treat a rental like their own home. After 2-3 years, you might face significant renovation costs due to wear and tear.</p>

<h3>Short-Term Rental</h3>
